Tutorial 2 - Building a CLI application with Clap

7 steps

It’s time for our first attempt at writing Rust code!

Our Rust project will allow you to learn on how to use clap featuring rusqlite as dependencies to build your CLI application.

NOTE: Getting rewards from this quest is over as it was only applicable on the Earn app when it was part of a campaign. Therefore, submissions are not reviewed or are disabled. However, you are highly encouraged to still complete the quest to practice your understanding.

For technical help on the StackUp platform & quest-related questions, join our Discord, head to the 🆘 | quest-help-forum channel and look for the correct thread to ask your question.
Join us on Discord

Helpful prior knowledge

Finished Tutorial 1 of Getting Your Hands Dirty with Rust in the Rust Learning Pathway.

Learning Outcomes

By the end of this tutorial, you will be able to:

  • Interface third-party crates into your Rust code
  • Demonstrate the effectiveness of using third-party crates
  • Create an application with clap and rusqlite

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 7

  • Step 1: Defining your application requirements

    It is important to note what your application requires once you are building software for yourself, and your team. In the future, you may come across questions like “Does it need to be fast? Does it require a lot of dependencies? Can we even create it despite our limited knowledge and resources?”

    Our project is a banking system application. However, it’s neither fancy nor applicable to real-world use. So most of its functionality is limited. With that said, why bother? Because it’s fun to learn programming that way ♥️

    Let’s just assume that this application is very important to us as a learning guide to Rust.

    Our banking app is simple. What it does is as follows:

    • Create accounts
    • Delete accounts

    And the menu has the following options

    1. Withdraw money
    2. Deposit money
    3. Transfer money to another account
    4. Check current balance of account
    5. Delete account
    6. Quitting the application

    What other requirements are we missing? Since we only talked about functionality, we should also describe how the functionalities work. For example, the following questions and answers might come to you: 🤔

    • How do we create and store the account? Using a database
    • How do we delete accounts? Communicating the database via commands
    • How do we create a Menu? Using the loop to break only once you select exit
    • How do we check the balance of an account? Fetching the records in the database
    • How do we transfer money from one account to another? Communicating the database via commands and altering the records

    The questions might not cover everything we wanted to ask but you can add more if you want. It’s important to find the right questions and narrow down the requirements of your applications. But for now, it’s a good idea to just follow along 😉

  • Step 2: Adding dependencies in cargo

    Now that we already defined our requirements, how do we make our application interact with the user? Since our goal for now is writing a CLI application, our first step is to think about what Rust has in its standard library. A command-line interface (CLI) suggests that we have to pass arguments such as flags and subcommands. For example, cargo has subcommands such as build, test and check. It also has --release as a flag for build, and other subcommands.

    Our application should also have its own subcommands for creating accounts, deleting accounts and logging into the menu. To do that, let’s add clap, a convenient command-line parser library to accommodate those subcommands. To add clap as your dependency, run the following command. 

    cargo add clap -F derive

    The -F flag is a short flag for --feature to enable features from a crate. Here, we enabled the derive feature of clap which allows us to inherit trait definitions from clap and lessen boilerplate code.

    We also need to store our created accounts somewhere and the best way to do it is using a database. We can use rusqlite for that. rusqlite is a convenient wrapper crate for SQLite. It allows us to use SQL commands effectively in Rust. To add rusqlite, run the following command

    cargo add rusqlite -F backup

    We included the backup feature so that we can re-access the database as we please while interacting with the application.

    Lastly, we add the rand crate so that our accounts are unique. To add rand, run the following command

    cargo add rand

    By now, you can check your manifest Cargo.toml file. Notice that it has been updated with the crates clap, rusqlite, and rand. It might look like this as shown below.

    [package]
name = "banking-system"
version = "0.1.0"
edition = "2021"

# See more keys and their definitions at https://doc.rust-lang.org/cargo/reference/manifest.html

[dependencies]
clap = { version = "4.5.4", features = ["derive"] }
rand = "0.8.5"
rusqlite = { version = "0.31.0", features = ["backup"] }
    Plain text

    So far we have added crates from the Rust Package Registry. However, what if we want a crate or a crate version that is not registered yet? We can have cargo to point to the Git repository of the upstream project. For example

    cargo add --git https://github.com/clap-rs/clap

    Most projects are now popularly using Git as their version control system that’s why cargo has an exclusive flag --git for it.

  • Step 3: Creating unique account numbers

    For our project, we need a way to generate unique account numbers. Therefore, we are going to use the Luhn algorithm to generate account numbers. You can read more about the Luhn algorithm in Wikipedia.

    First, let’s create a file at src/luhn.rs.

    Here, we are splitting the parts of our code as separate modules instead of putting it in main.rs. The reason behind this is to encourage code organisation.

    In Rust, a module is a namespace that contains definitions of functions, types, traits, and other modules.

    Modules allow you to organise your code logically into separate units, making it more manageable, understandable, and reusable. They help in structuring larger projects by breaking them into smaller, more manageable parts.

    You can imagine this as a knitted stuff toy vs legos shown below as two photos.

    The first picture is a whole item. If damaged, they are harder to replace and repair. We can’t even use any parts for other toys. The second picture has parts that can be used by others and even replaced. Like the toy legos, modularity of your code allows you to reuse parts of your code with less of a negative impact to the overall code.

    It’s good practice to start separating your code of different functionalities in mind e.g. when the project gets too big.

    To continue, you might want to try to implement the Luhn algorithm yourself. Or you can copy the code for src/luhn.rs. See Github Gist Link. You can scroll down to the bottom of the page so you can see the entirety of the code. Don’t close the page as you will be needing it to finish this quest!

  • Step 4: Storing created accounts

    Next, we may want to store information for account numbers, their pins, and their balances. An SQL database such as sqlite is a good and lightweight solution. We can use it via the Rust crate rusqlite. Now let’s create our src/database.rs file

    Our goal is to create accounts, delete accounts, deposit money into accounts, withdraw money from accounts, transfer money between accounts, and lastly, check the remaining balance of the accounts. Most of those operations also require a PIN.

    You might want to implement this yourself, or copy the code snippets and paste it into src/database.rs. See Github Gist Link.

  • Step 5: Creating the menu

    Now that we all have the functions to interact with the database, we need to implement the command-line arguments to interact with the functions and with the user. Let’s create a src/menu.rs file

    Our banking app is simple. What it does is described as follows:

    • Create accounts
    • Delete accounts

    Menu has the following options:

    • Withdraw money
    • Deposit money
    • Transfer money to another account
    • Check current balance of account
    • Delete account
    • Quitting the application

    Some of these operations require a PIN, a security challenge for the user. In an ideal world, only the owner knows of the PIN.

    You might want to implement the menu yourself. Or you can copy the code. See Github Gist link.

  • Step 6: Finalising the CLI and run your application

    As you might have noticed, writing code to parse additional command line arguments is a daunting repetitive task. We will use clap to solve our issues.

    Clap is a fully featured command line argument parser. It allows us to easily define short flags or long flags of arguments e.g. verbose might have --verbose or -v.

    It also allows us to easily define sections of structs and enums using the derive attribute. In Rust, derive is a feature that allows you to automatically implement certain traits for your custom data types (structs and enums). This feature is enabled through the #[derive] attribute placed before the declaration of the data type.

    When you derive a trait for a struct or enum, the Rust compiler automatically generates the implementation code for that trait based on the structure of your data type. This can save you from writing repetitive boilerplate code. A good example of this is deriving the Debug trait.

    #[derive(Debug)] // We told the compiler that it has "derived" the trait Debug
struct Person { age: u32 }
    Rust

    In our case, clap can enable the feature to use derive attributes to lessen boilerplate code for parsing CLI arguments as structured data e.g. structs, enums.

    To accomplish this in our CLI code with clap, let’s create a new file called src/cli.rs.

    You might want to implement this on your own. But you can also copy the code. See Github Gist Link.

    We need to create an entry point to integrate all those functionality at src/main.rs. Before that we need to edit src/lib.rs first. Copy the code below for src/lib.rs.

    // SPDX-License-Identifier: Unlicense

pub mod cli;
pub mod database;
pub mod luhn;
pub mod menu;
    Rust

    Our main.rs file contains code that calls for the following functionality

    • Users can create account through the command line arguments and make sure it isn’t a duplicate
    • Users are able to login into the menu
    • Users can delete account through the command line arguments
    • Each operation requires the correct PIN for an account

    Let’s celebrate now that we have finally finished building our application 🥳

    • Transfer money to another account.

    Your screenshot should show:

    • your full screen, including your taskbar (for Windows and Linux) / dock (for MacOS)
    • your main.rs is an opened file and clearly shown.
    • your terminal emulator showing the interaction on deposit and transfer of money.
    • your file explorer opened showing the files and folders of the project
    • make sure that all parts visible in the expected output below are also visible in your screenshot

    ℹ️ For non-VSCode or non-VSCode-fork users, you can show the file contents using your file manager and a separate terminal.

    Refer to the image if you are unsure. If the image is too small, right click on the image and press on 'Open Image in New Tab'.

    When labelling your screenshot, make sure to follow the format provided C26_Q2_yourusername.png.

    ℹ️ In the event that your screen is not wide enough to accommodate multiple windows side by side, you may take the screenshots separately and then merge them into one image.

    You can use any editing tool for that e.g. using Powerpoint to merge them on Windows, using Preview on MacOS/OSX or using Imagemagick on Linux e.g. running the following command

    convert image23.png image18.png +append C26_Q3_yourusername.png

    Or use a web tool such as https://www.adobe.com/express/feature/image/combine.
